ina, and indigenous Canadian artists such as Nadia Myre and Michèle Taïna Audette, showing how socially engaged art catalyzes forms of resistance that operate beyond the institutional art world. From the Americas and Europe to Iran and South Africa, Kester presents a historical genealogy of recent engaged art practices rooted in a deep history of cultural production, beginning with nineteenth-century political struggles and continuing into contemporary anticolonial resistance and other social movements.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aArt and societyxHistoryy20th century. 0aArt criticism. 0aArtxPhilosophy. 0aArt, ModernxPolitical aspects. 0aAutonomy (Psychology) in art. 0aAvant-garde (Aesthetics)xHistoryy20th century. 0aSubjectivity in art. 7aART / Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311135689140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478027478?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478027478423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478027478/original  a978-3-11-135689-1  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles